  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "Welcome, Player.\nIn this place, everything is powered by truth and logic.\n\nTo
    restore the Logic Pillar, you must master the Truth Tables.\n\nWhat is a Truth
    Table?\nA truth table is a table that shows all possible truth values of logical
    statements.\nIn Computer Science:\nUsed in Boolean algebra\nUsed in Digital circuits\nUsed
    in Programming conditions\nUsed in AI decision systems\nThere are only two truth
    values:\nSymbol       Meaning\nT                     True (1)\nF                     
    False (0)\nThink of it like binary:\n1 = True\n0 = False\n\nProposition\nObjective:
    Understand what a proposition is?\nA proposition is a statement that is either
    true or false, but not both.\nExamples:\nStatement.         Proposition?\n\"2
    + 2 = 4\".               Yes\n\"It is raining.\".           Yes\n\"Close the
    door.\".     No (command)\n\"How are you?\".       No (question)\nOnly propositions
    can be used in truth tables.\n\n\nNegation ( NOT )\nSymbol: \xACp\nMeaning: \"NOT
    p\"\nIf p is true \u2192 \xACp is false\nIf p is false \u2192 \xACp is true\nTruth
    Table:\np.       \xACp\nT.        F\nF.        T\n Example:\nLet\np: \"The server
    is online.\"\nIf p = T\nThen \xACp = \"The server is not online.\" \u2192 F\n\n\nDisjunction
    ( OR )\nSymbol: p \u2228 q\nMeaning: \"p OR q\"\nAt least one must be TRUE.\nTruth
    Table:\np.        q.        p \u2228 q\nT.        T.            T\nT.       
    F.            T\nF.        T.            T\nF.        F.            F\nImportant:
    This is inclusive OR, not exclusive.\nSo:\nT, T = True\nOnly false if both are
    false\n\n\n\nConjunction ( AND )\nSymbol: p \u2227 q\nMeaning: \"p AND q\"\nBoth
    must be TRUE to be TRUE.\nTruth Table:\np.         q.        p \u2227 q\nT.         
    T.           T\nT.          F.           F\nF.          T.           F\nF.         
    F.           F\nThink of this like:\nif (condition1 and condition2):\n    execute()\nBoth
    must pass.\n\n\nImplication ( IF\u2026THEN )\r\nSymbol: p \u2192 q\r\nMeaning:
    \"If p, then q\"\r\nThis one confuses many students \U0001F440 so listen carefully.\r\nRule:\r\nIt
    is FALSE only when:\r\np = TRUE\r\nq = FALSE\r\nTruth Table:\r\np.          
    q.       p \u2192 q\r\nT.           T.           T\r\nT.           F.          
    F\r\nF.           T.           T\r\nF.           F.           T\r\nWhy is F \u2192
    F = True?\r\nBecause if the first part (p) is false, the statement makes no promise.\r\nIn
    programming terms:\r\nif p:\r\n    must_do_q()\r\nIf p never happens, you never
    break the rule.\n\n\n\nBiconditional ( IF AND ONLY IF )\r\nSymbol: p \u2194 q\r\nMeaning:\r\np
    is true if and only if q is true\r\nThey must have the same truth value.\r\nTruth
    Table:\r\np.           q.        p \u2194 q\r\nT.           T.             T\r\nT.          
    F.             F\r\nF.           T.             F\r\nF.           F.            
    T\r\nTrue when both match\r\n False when different\r\nYou can also think of it
    as:\r\n\r\n(p \u2192 q) AND (q \u2192 p)"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: b86979d84307d064da1c84f6fcc3eb3e, type: 2}
